    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-07-13T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-07-13T00:00:00-05:00" n="28"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d28">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72/6</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Vice Consul General at Budapest</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="#p_MFE1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Mallett</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <dateline>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Consulate General</hi>, <lb/>
                    <placeName>
                        <hi rend="italic">Budapest</hi>
                    </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-07-13">
                        <hi rend="italic">July 13, 1914</hi>.</date>
                    <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received July 27</hi>.] </dateline>
                <p>The impression prevails at present in Budapest that a war between Austria-Hungary
                    and Servia is unavoidable, and that hostilities will begin soon after the crops
                    are harvested.</p>
                <p>Although the Budapest newspapers have been forbidden by the military authorities
                    to publish any news in regard to mobilization, it is known nevertheless to quite
                    a number of persons in Budapest that two or three army corps are being mobilized
                    at present near the Servian frontier in Hungary and in Bosnia.</p>
                <p>The newspapers have also been forbidden to publish anything in regard to a
                    military cordon, which will be established along the frontier between Servia and
                    Austria-Hungary. The purpose of this military cordon is to prevent desertions of
                    Servians who are in the Austro-Hungarian Army and to prevent the entrance into
                    Bosnia of Servians. The Hungarian Minister of War has issued an order forbidding
                    the sale of horses to Servians or to any foreigners.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_MFE1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">F. E. Mallett</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
